zed a regolith sample from a cometary nucleus in situ,\nwhile Ptolemy measured cometary gas from the ambient coma. The m/z 44 peak\nmeasured by COSAC was likely dominated by organic species, whereas the peak\nmeasured by Ptolemy was interpreted to be mostly due to $CO_2$. Ion species\nheavier than m/z 30 tend to decay somewhat slower in the COSAC measurements\nthan in the Ptolemy data, which may be related to differences in the exhaust\ndesigns between both instruments.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 1 Feb 2017 10:26:41 GMT"}],"update_date":"2017-04-05"}
